******
[1] Virginia
Date: Mon 24 Feb 2020
Source: WSET [edited]
https://wset.com/news/local/horse-in-virginia-tests-positive-for-equine-herpesvirus-1-02-24-2020


A horse in Virginia has tested positive for equine herpesvirus-1 (EHV-1). According to the Virginia Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services (VDACS), on [Fri 21 Feb 2020], the state veterinarian's office of the VDACS confirmed one horse tested positive for EHV-1. The infected horse was at a boarding stable in Powhatan County. The boarding stable has been placed under quarantine. They say no horse had left the property in at least 2 weeks.

In addition, the VDACS says exposed horses are being monitored twice daily for fever (temperature over 101.50 deg F; 38.6 deg C) and other clinical signs, and no additional Virginia horses have been exposed. There is no cause for alarm concerning the general horse population in Virginia.

EHV-1 is a virus present in the environment and found in most horses all over the world. Horses typically are exposed to the virus at a young age with no serious side effects. A large percentage of horses carry the virus with no clinical signs for the remainder of their lives. Rarely, exposed horses develop the neurologic form of the disease.

Horse owners with concerns should contact their veterinarian. The Equine Disease Communications Center has more information on best practices for disease prevention in horses (http://www.equinediseasecc.org/biosecurity), and VDACS has more information on EHV-1 (http://www.vdacs.virginia.gov/animals-equine-herpes-virus.shtml).

Horse owners also may contact VDACS' Office of Veterinary Services at 804-786-2483.

[byline: Ida Domingo]

